item.title: About
item.dc:creator: localhost
item.content:encoded:
Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s is a non-profit, support and educational organization designated by the IRS as a 501 (c) 3 tax-deductible, tax-exempt organization. This organization was founded in 2013 in celebration of Amanda Hope’s life that ended all too soon when she lost her battle against Leukemia. During her four year fight, Amanda Hope dreamed that one day she would design a fun clothing line for kids in the same type of situation that would provide comfort and dignity during treatment. Here is Amanda Hope’s dream!

Our Mission:

Bring dignity and comfort into the harsh world of childhood cancer and other life-threatening diseases.

Our Vision:

  1. Provide Comfycozy’s Care™ gifts to all children diagnosed with cancer and other blood-related disorders.
  2. Support healthcare professionals in providing person-centered care to children and their families with empathy and understanding.
  3. Help families have voice and choice above harsh protocols often present in the healthcare system.

Problem – Children and Families in Crisis

In 2012, an estimated 16,000 new diagnoses of cancer are expected to occur among children 0 to 14 years of age. When a child is diagnosed with cancer or life-threatening illness, fear and shock ensues. Parents and family members are immediately faced with overwhelming decisions and issues regarding the care and well-being of their child. Often spanning months and years, the child’s treatment becomes the center of the family’s universe. The strength they will need for this battle is second only to the fear for their child’s life. The physical, emotional, spiritual and financial toll that this horrible disease and other life-threatening illnesses have on children and their families is unimaginable – until you are there. Provided by an endless stream of healthcare professionals, the myriad of appointments, tests, procedures and potential surgeries endured by the child and family only contributes to the family’s loss of voice, dignity, modesty and control.

Solution – Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s

Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s will provide support to children and their families dealing with cancer and other life-threatening diseases through the following three programs. The geographic scope has begun in Arizona at Phoenix Children’s Hospital. Contingent on funding and philanthropy, Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s will expand to other major pediatric hospitals throughout the nation such as St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital, Seattle Children’s Hospital and Children’s National Medical Center.

I. Comfycozy’s Care™ Gifts

Who? All children diagnosed with cancer or blood-related illness will receive a Comfycozy’s Care Gift. What? Comfycozy’s Care™ Gifts are bright, washable backpacks that contain Comfycozy’s T-Shirts that are specially designed with zippers, pockets and holes allowing healthcare professionals access to a child’s ports and tubes while the child’s body remains covered. Providing dignity for the Journey. These T-shirts are in fun tie-dye colors, come in every size imaginable and the kids, families and healthcare professionals love them already! This gift package also includes educational material for the family, supportive material about community resources and other “fun stuff” just for the child. When? Now! In December 2012, all children diagnosed with cancer or blood-related illness receiving out-patient and in-patient services at Phoenix Children’s Hospital received a Comfycozy’s Care™ gift package. All children receiving these same services at Cardon Children’s Hospital in Scottsdale will receive Comfycozy’s Care™ gift packages in February, 2013.

II. Supporting Health Care Professionals

Who? The care and treatment provided by health care professionals (i.e., physicians, nurses, technicians and office and hospital personnel, etc.) has a tremendous impact on the health and well-being of the child and their family. While the treatment protocols these professionals follow are of the utmost importance, it is also imperative that empathy and dignity be a priority at all times in all environments. What? Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s will develop and distribute educational material focused on helping medical professionals understand person-centered care, the strengths of the child and family, and the fear the family is experiencing. Workshops and presentations will be conducted at health care professional conferences, trade shows and meetings to discuss the importance of supporting family voice and dignity through empathy and understanding. When? In 2013, our volunteer ‘Angels’ will interact directly with families, health care professionals and hospital and clinic personnel while distributing Comfycozy’s Care™ Gifts to 1) provide written and verbal information, 2) identify opportunities for developing and providing additional materials and information and 3) identify health care professionals who practice this model and can support others.

III. Helping Families Have Voice and Choice

Who? It is vital for families to understand that they are their child’s advocate –no-one else can take their place in this role. Families must have voice and choice in their child’s healthcare decisions and not be afraid to challenge healthcare protocols, professionals and insurance companies. What? Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s will provide advocacy support through community resources, a hotline, volunteer advocates and other supports. We will also provide financial assistance to families in need such as utility payments, childcare, etc. Win Win. All Comfycozy’s for chemo are made by 2 organizations: “Dresses for Orphans” who make clothes for orphans in 22 countries around the world and “Poonman Designs” who’s mission is to rescue young women from domestic violence and the sex trade Industry in India. Giving the dignity and training to make a better life for them and there children. When? As soon as we receive your help and support.

MEET THE BOARD

 

Lorraine Tallman

Founder and Executive Director

Lorraine is the driving force behind Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s and Comfycozy’s for Chemo. Her personal experience in the pediatric cancer treatment world, sparked her lifelong devotion to advocacy and support for children with cancer and their families. She is committed to fulfilling Amanda’s last wish to provide dignity and empowerment to every Oncology and Hematology patient through the gift of their very own Comfycozy. She is a member of the Steering Committee for the Arizona Childhood Cancer Coalition. She serves on the Family Advisory Council and the Memorial Service Grievance Committee at Phoenix Children’s Hospital. She also teaches the ‘Family Centered Care’ class to their new healthcare professionals. She is a sought after speaker for Mother’s Grace, MASK magazine, the Child Life Specialist Association, and many other organizations. Currently, she is collaborating with C.R. Bard, an international medical device company, on the development of a medical port needle device for easy one-time access. By limiting the number of pokes the patient’s anxiety and discomfort are reduced.  

Herman Lewkowitz

President

Herman is a Senior Private Banker for CoBiz Private Bank’s Arizona market. He is a member of the Board of Directors of the First Tee of Phoenix, as well as a member of the board and on the Investment Committee for the Crisis Nursery Foundation and a Life Member of the Thunderbirds. Herman is married with three kids and is devoted to helping pediatric cancer patients via the Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s foundation. He earned a BSBA from the University of Arizona double majoring in Finance & Real Estate; and an MBA from Arizona State University.  

Kathryn Marchwick

Secretary

Kathryn is a CFP and Investment Advisory Representative in the Greater Phoenix Metropolitan area with over 30 years of investment and financial planning experience. She is currently affiliated with Williams Financial Broker Dealer as an Independent Representative and Financial Planner. She serves as a member of the Financial Planning Council at Blessed Sacrament in Scottsdale, Arizona. Kathryn earned an Associates Degree from the Kenosha Memorial Hospital School of Histotechnology and attended the University of Wisconsin Parkside.  

Marty Tallman

Founder, Treasurer, Planned Giving and Endowment Committee Chair

“The Original Comfycozy” First and Foremost, Amanda’s loving Dad (Non-Biological) and Lorraine’s adoring Husband! Way too early in our life together, our sole focus became the healing of Amanda and as importantly assuring Amanda’s comfort and dignity throughout her Battle with Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia. We Founded ComFycozy’s to full fill Amanda’s Dream to give every child a comfortable shirt that allowed them to receive their Chemo treatments without undressing. We founded Amanda Hope Rainbow Angels to expand our family assistance and the Gift of “Comfycozy’s” to every child! Marty Graduated from the University of San Diego, with a BA Degree in accounting and a Minor in Leadership. He has founded import/export, Real Estate and Mortgage Broker companies.  

Tom Garrity

Public Relations Committee Chair

Tom is currently the CEO and President of the Stampede, Sioux Falls Sports, LLC and Quan Sports Marketing, LLC. Previously he was the SVP of Sales for the Houston Astros, the President of the Houston Aeros and Team President of the Cincinnati Mighty Ducks. He has also been affiliated with the Canaries baseball team, the Capitols hockey team and the Minnesota Wild hockey team. Tom was recently named United States Hockey League executive of the year 2014-2015. Tom provides a direction connection for us to numerous teams in the sports industry resulting in team and player support. He earned his degree from the University of Wisconsin at Platteville.  

Susan Reina

Family-Centered Care Committee Chair

Susan is a Physician Assistant at Nextcare Urgent Care in Flagstaff and Phoenix. Working in research for the National Institutes of Health fostered her dedication to the healthcare industry. As committee chair, Susan provides leadership for the development and implementation of our “Person Centered Care” curriculum, designed for the Healthcare Providers specializing in pediatric cancer. Susan earned her undergrad degree from Northern Arizona University and her masters in physician assistant studies from AT Still University.  

Garth Price

Board Member

Garth is currently the Chief Executive Officer of Sunstate Equipment, Co., and a former Certified Public Accountant and Manager with Deloitte & Touche. Throughout his life Mr. Price has been active in his community where he has served in various capacities including the Executive Council of the Boys and Girls Clubs, the Audit Committee of a community bank, a member of the Executive Leadership Team of the Arizona American Heart Association, and an owner of Flip Dunk Sports, LLC, a trampoline and gymnastics center. As a member of the board, Garth provides leadership and experience that will help Amanda Hope Rainbow Angel’s develop further as a non-profit organization. Garth received his Bachelor of Science in Accountancy from Northern Arizona University.
